            "DetailedDescription": "\n<h2><strong>Grid Creator</strong></h2>\n\n<p>The Grid Creator vTool creates a grid overlay that divides an image into individual cells. When the image is passed on for further processing, subsequent vTools can evaluate the contents of the individual cells instead of the image as a whole.\n</p>\n<p>To design the grid, you have to specify the number of rows and columns and the height and width of the individual cells. You can also configure whether you want the grid to cover the whole image or just a part of it. By default, the grid starts at the top left pixel of the image. By specifying an offset, you can place the grid where your region of interest begins.\n</p>\n<p><strong>Prerequisites</strong>\n    <ul>\n        <li>The size of the images has to remain constant in your application. If image sizes vary, the grid may not fit anymore.</li>\n        <li>Before you can configure the Grid Creator vTool, you have to connect its <strong>Image</strong> input pin to an <strong>Image</strong> output pin of another vTool.</li>\n    </ul> \n</p>\n<p>\n    Here is a brief overview of how to use the vTool:\n<ol>\n    <li>Connect its <strong>Image</strong> input pin to the <strong>Image</strong> output pin of another vTool.</li>\n    <li>Select the Grid Creator vTool in the Workbench.</li>\n    <li>Open the <strong>Features - All</strong> pane.</li>\n    <li>Expand the <strong>vTool</strong> group.</li>\n    <li>Count the number of columns and rows you need and enter the values in the <strong>Number of Columns</strong> and <strong>Number of Rows</strong> parameters accordingly.</li>\n    <li>If you want your grid to cover the entire image, select the <strong>Auto Size Grid</strong> parameter.<br>This allows the vTool to divide the image into cells based on the number of columns and rows you have specified. If you need a smaller grid, continue with the next step.</li>\n    <li>Determine the width and height of the individual cells and enter the values in the <strong>Cell Width</strong> and <strong>Cell Height</strong> parameters accordingly.<br>See tip below.</li>\n    <li>Specify a horizontal and vertical offset.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Tip</strong></p>\n<p>\n    If you enable the <strong>Regions</strong> output pin, an overlay is displayed over the input image showing the different regions, i.e., cells. This allows you to immediately see the effects of your configuration in the pin data view while the recipe is running. To do this:\n    <ol>\n        <li>Select the <strong>Regions Output Pin</strong> parameter.</li>\n        <li>Open a pin data view and select the <strong>Image</strong> pin of the image source vTool and the <strong>Regions</strong> pin of the Grid Creator.</li>\n        <li>Start the recipe.</li>\n    </ol>\n    You may have to play around with the settings a little to make the grid fit. If you hover with your mouse over a pixel in the image, the status bar of the pin data view shows you the coordinates of that pixel (X/Y). This should help finding the right settings. \n</p>\n</p>\n<p><br></p>\n<h3>\n    <strong>Inputs</strong>\n</h3>\n<p>\n    <strong>Image:</strong> Accepts images directly from a Camera vTool or any other vTool that outputs images.\n</p>\n\n<p><br></p>\n<h3>\n    <strong>Outputs</strong>\n</h3>\n<p>\n    <strong>Rectangles:</strong> Returns a rectangle for each cell of the grid.\n</p>\n<p>\n    <strong>Regions:</strong> Returns the number of regions in the grid and visualizes the regions in the image.\n</p>\n\n<p><br></p>\n<h3>\n    <strong>Configuring the vTool</strong>\n</h3>\n<p>\n  Double-click the vTool to open a settings dialog. This is a graphical representation of the vTool's parameters.\n</p>\n<p>\n  You can also configure the vTool via the pylon API and the <strong>Features - All</strong> pane of the pylon Viewer.\n  All parameters listed there can be set via the pylon API. To study the effects of a parameter, change the parameter\n  values in the <strong>Features - All</strong> pane and watch the results in a pin data view when running the recipe.\n  For more details about parameters, select a parameter and check the <strong>Feature Documentation</strong> pane.\n</p>\n<p><br></p>\n<p>\n    <a href=\"pylonVToolGridCreator\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\"><u>Get help</u></a>\n</p>",
